'''''X-Wing: The Bacta War''''' is the fourth installment in the [[Star Wars: X-Wing (novel series)|''X-Wing'']] series of novels, released in [[February]] [[1997]] by [[Bantam Spectra]]. It is a science fiction novel written by [[Michael A. Stackpole]]. [[Anthony Heald]] narrated the audio version.

==Publisher's summary==
''While the Alliance fleet mounts a major campaign against a deadly warlord, Ysanne Isard has seized control of Thyferra, intending to use its precious supply of bacta to destabilize and destroy the New Republic. It falls to Rogue Squadron - undermanned, deprived of Alliance support and even weapons - to oppose Isard's dangerous designs, defeat her powerful complement of Star Destroyers, and free Thyferra from her iron rule. But when Isard discovers the Squadron's secret base, its ragtag group of pilots must scramble for survival in a winner-take-all battle against Isard's overwhelming and seemingly superior force.''

==Plot summary==
[[Thyferra/Legends|Thyferra]] is [[The galaxy/Legends|the galaxy's]] principal source of [[Bacta/Legends|bacta]]. Production and distribution of the healing agent has traditionally been managed by two ruling corporations – [[Xucphra Corporation|Xucphra]] and [[Zaltin Corporation|Zaltin]]. Zaltin has staged a coup on the [[Planet/Legends|planet]] and installed [[Ysanne Isard]] as its ruler. [[Politics/Legends|Politically]], the [[New Republic/Legends|New Republic]] cannot intervene in a strictly Thyferran matter. Determined to oust Isard, [[Rogue Squadron/Legends|Rogue Squadron]] resigns from active duty.

Basing their operation on a [[Space station/Legends|space station]] over [[Yag'Dhul/Legends|Yag'dhul]], the Rogues call in favors and scour the black market to supply their mission. [[Corran Horn/Legends|Corran]] meets [[Mirax Terrik Horn|Mirax's]] [[Parent/Legends|father]], the legendary [[Smuggler/Legends|smuggler]] [[Booster Terrik]]. Aided by Zaltin rebels, sympathetic [[Twi'lek/Legends|Twi'leks]], and [[Mercenary/Legends|mercenary]] allies, the Rogues begin raiding bacta convoys and redistributing the captured medicine freely to planets. Isard retaliates by targeting the worlds benefitting from Rogue Squadron's vigilantism. These violent exchanges culminate in Isard attacking Thyferra directly to eliminate the rebellious factions there, which costs her several key allies. By luring Isard's forces to their Yag'dhul's base, the Rogues provoke a confrontation with the [[Lusankya/Legends|''Lusankya'']] [[Executor-class Star Dreadnought/Legends|Super Star Destroyer]]. When New Republic reinforcements suddenly arrive, the [[Galactic Empire/Legends|Imperials]] retreat, surrendering the [[Imperial II-class Star Destroyer/Legends|Star Destroyer]] [[Errant Venture/Legends|''Virulence'']] as the ''Lusankya'' returns to Thyferra.

In a final battle over Thyferra, Corran shots down the traitorous [[Erisi Dlarit]]. Overwhelmed by superior tactics, the Imperials aboard the ''Lusankya'' surrender, and [[Tycho Celchu/Legends|Tycho]] blasts the [[Shuttle/Legends|shuttle]] believed to be ferrying Ysanne. The Rogues are disappointed to discover that the [[Prisoner/Legends|prisoners]] aboard the ''Lusankya'' have been secreted elsewhere. Rogue Squadron's original designation is conveniently lost in a bureaucratic mishap. [[Wedge Antilles/Legends|Wedge Antilles]] assumes command of the ''Lusankya'', and the grand [[Warship/Legends|warship]] is the setting for the wedding of Mirax Terrik and Corran Horn. Booster Terrik now owns the captured Star Destroyer Virulence, and this great prize helps to offset any misgivings he may have about his daughter marring a former lawman.

==Continuity==
The cover of the novel does not match the text. In the book, Rogue Squadron does not battle all of Ysanne Isard's Star Destroyers, and no Mon Calamari frigates helped in the Bacta War.

